// SUSPECTED GAP — spawn allows aliased pointers to the same global
//
// Pattern: `spawn worker(&g, &g);` — both args point to the same global.
//
// ZER's spawn rule:
//   - non-shared pointer to spawn = compile error (data race)
//   - scoped spawn with ThreadHandle allows *T args (will be joined)
//
// The scoped-spawn path validates each arg individually but never compares
// arg identities. Two pointers to the same global silently compile.
//
// Why it's a real gap:
//   1. Callee may rely on parameter independence (no aliasing assumption)
//   2. Worker can use `a` and `b` paths concurrently → undefined behavior
//      under strict aliasing
//   3. Main thread also still has `&g` available between spawn and join —
//      data race with worker's writes through both `a` and `b`
//
// Even with shared struct, &shared g passed twice is questionable: the
// auto-lock fires once per access, but the function signature implies
// `a` and `b` are independent state.

shared struct S { u32 v; }
S g;

void worker(*shared S a, *shared S b) {
    a.v = 1;
    b.v = 2;
}

i32 main() {
    ThreadHandle th = spawn worker(&g, &g);  // EXPECTED: warning or error
    th.join();
    return 0;
}
